  "timeframe": "4H / 1D (with 15m for entries)",
  "market_context": "The analyst demonstrates how he applies the Box Setup methodology on higher time frames in ES to establish directional bias for range trading, then drills down to lower time frames for execution.",
  "key_observation": "On the 4-hour, the analyst uses candle bodies to mark the range and tracks deviations from it; on the daily, he switches to using wicks. Deviations from the range on either time frame define his bias.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 4-hour chart, identify an old high marking out the body of the range.",
    "Step 2: Observe a move higher with a nice close above the level, followed by an aggressive move lower and a retest — marking out the deviation from the range.",
    "Step 3: Identify a second similar flow on the 4-hour where price deviates from the range, reinforcing the bias.",
    "Step 4: Switch to the daily time frame and use the wicks (rather than bodies) to mark the range.",
    "Step 5: Look for the deviation from the range on the daily to confirm higher-time-frame bias.",
    "Step 6: Drop down to the 15-minute time frame to find specific entry setups aligned with the established HTF bias."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "For bias on the 4-hour, use candle bodies to define the range; on the daily, use wicks. Deviations from these ranges provide directional bias, and lower time frames like 15-minute are then used to find aligned entries.",
